label: HH1

text: Reuben Elementary was rich with learning and excitement in 2005-06 for teachers as
label: BODY

text: well as students.  Teachers utilized a new initiative of the district (Early Release Days) to
label: BODY

text: participate in team planning and data analysis.  Curriculum mapping was the focus early
label: BODY

text: in the year that helped all grade levels get a better picture of the standards covered in
label: BODY

text: each grade and how these standards build upon each other from year too year.  A local
label: BODY

text: company donated 15 refurbished laptops to the school, making it possible for the
label: BODY

text: teachers to incorporate technology in their lessons and in their professional lives.  Eight
label: BODY

text: teachers took graduate level courses to earn advanced degrees.  These endeavors
label: BODY

text: created collaborative conversations and planning among the staff, which led to a new
label: BODY

text: energy and improved instruction in the classrooms.
label: BODY

text: Students were engaged in small group instruction meeting individual needs in all
label: BODY

text: classrooms.  Grades 2-5 took Measures of Academic Progress (MAP) twice during the
label: BODY

text: year and gave teachers academic progress that guided the instruction.  During the year
label: BODY

text: the students participated in artistic fieldtrips to plays and ballets.  Some classes visited
label: BODY

text: museums or the State House.  Our fifth grade took its traditional trip to Washington, D.C.
label: BODY

text: in the fall of 2005.  Poet Brod Baggert left the students with a huge impression of poetry
label: BODY

text: and entertained the student body by reading his poems.  One fifth-grade student was
label: BODY

text: recognized by the State for her artwork being selected for use in the 2006 Safe Kids
label: BODY

text: Calendar.  Eight students became certified Junior Master Gardeners.

label: BODY
